984
00:55:49,690 --> 00:55:51,891
in only its stereotypical way,

985
00:55:51,931 --> 00:55:53,631
we would never have had the opening of The Rite of Spring,

986
00:55:53,671 --> 00:55:55,372
which no one had ever heard a bassoon really play

987
00:55:55,392 --> 00:55:58,393
that high and gently and weirdly lyrically like that.

988
00:55:58,473 --> 00:56:02,694
And so it's sort of a tug of war between these two poles.

989
00:56:02,734 --> 00:56:04,474
In the specific case, for example, of the bucca horn,

990
00:56:04,494 --> 00:56:06,395
the weird lamb's horn, I think, and literally,

991
00:56:06,415 --> 00:56:10,436
it only plays a kind of quasi-modal F-sharp minor

992
00:56:10,456 --> 00:56:12,877
that is not at all based around like an A440-derived.

993
00:56:15,051 --> 00:56:19,855
It's just kind of like, yeah, this is the closest note to F sharp that I would call that sound.

994
00:56:20,956 --> 00:56:24,559
And so yes, I very quickly realized I have to write to what this thing can do.

995
00:56:24,579 --> 00:56:28,802
Because I can, one note wrong, if I write a G natural, he'll go, I can't do it.

996
00:56:29,723 --> 00:56:36,729
You know, so that very much did dictate a lot of what I was doing in certain areas.

997
00:56:37,249 --> 00:56:39,971
